  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Hyulgu Temple
  author: Yu Seungdan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten days' journey compressed into one,
    the sky hangs low, barely a hand's span away.
    Even on rainy nights the moon remains visible,
    on windy days no dust settles on the path.
    New moon and full moon mark the calendar by tide,
    the grasses measure the seasons by heat and cold.
    When I look upon the world, I see only war and strife—
    how I envy those who sleep among the clouds.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The compression of distance and lowering of sky suggest a spiritual sanctuary removed from worldly concerns.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to natural cycles (tides, seasonal grasses) indicates a place where cosmic order remains intact and observable.
  - key: ''
    value: The closing contrast between the turmoil of the world and the peace of those dwelling in clouds reflects a common Buddhist and Daoist ideal of withdrawal from society.
